  "prompt": "How do I solve [math]\\displaystyle\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3}+x)[/math]?",
  "response": "To solve the limit \n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x\\to \\infty}\\left(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x\\right)\n\\]\n\nwe start with simplifying the term \\( \\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} \\).\n\nAs \\( x \\to \\infty \\), the term inside the cube root can be expressed as:\n\n\\[\nx^2 - x^3 = -x^3 (1 - \\frac{2}{x}) = -x^3 (1 - o(1)),\n\\]\n\nbecause \\( \\frac{2}{x} \\to 0 \\) as \\( x \\to \\infty \\).\n\nNow, we apply the cube root:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3(1 - o(1))} = \\sqrt[3]{-x^3} \\sqrt[3]{1 - o(1)} = -x \\sqrt[3]{1 - o(1)}.\n\\]\n\nWe can approximate \\( \\sqrt[3]{1 - o(1)} \\) for large \\( x \\) as follows:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{1 - o(1)} \\approx 1 \\quad \\text{as } x \\to \\infty.\n\\]\n\nThus,\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} \\approx -x.\n\\]\n\nPutting everything together in the limit:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x \\approx -x + x = 0.\n\\]\n\nTo be precise, we confirm this by writing:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = -x \\cdot \\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{2}{x}}.\n\\]\n\nFor large \\( x \\),\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{1 - \\frac{2}{x}} = 1 - \\frac{2}{3x} + o\\left(\\frac{1}{x}\\right).\n\\]\n\nThus, we find\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} = -x\\left(1 - \\frac{2}{3x} + o\\left(\\frac{1}{x}\\right)\\right) = -x + \\frac{2}{3} + o(1).\n\\]\n\nCombining gives:\n\n\\[\n\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x = \\left(-x + \\frac{2}{3} + o(1)\\right) + x = \\frac{2}{3} + o(1).\n\\]\n\nTaking the limit \\( x \\to \\infty \\):\n\n\\[\n\\lim_{x \\to \\infty} \\left(\\sqrt[3]{x^2 - x^3} + x\\right) = \\frac{2}{3}.\n\\]\n\nThus, the final result for the limit is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\frac{2}{3}}.\n\\]",
